WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.560
Good afternoon. So, many of you probably have seen or tried to help a workplace adopt R.

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:19.400
So this is the typical case I see. Your company hired an R trainer, went over a lot of fancy

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:25.200
things possible in R with the team. After the training, everyone finds R very cool.

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:31.680
Tidyverse, amazing. R Markdown, awesome. Shiny, fantastic. But then after a few days,

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:35.200
most people just went back to the go-to tools. I'd rather not call it out, but something

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:41.360
that's not R. Several years ago, my company moved to R, and we faced the same situation.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:47.680
To help change that, I initiated a work automation project with R, and now we have 20-plus team

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:52.880
members who consider R the go-to tools, 60-plus stakeholders who use our product on a daily

00:00:52.880 --> 00:01:00.080
basis, and this has saved over 12,000 hours and counting. In the next 15 minutes, I'm

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:04.199
going to talk about key parts of the project, lessons learned, and the structure you could

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:10.739
follow if you would like to implement it. Now, let's revisit the situation. We want

00:01:10.739 --> 00:01:17.080
to move things to R, but why aren't there many movements? Well, we all have learning

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:23.040
curve as beginners. Some of us went through it quicker. More of us don't. The other scenario

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:29.500
I can think of is that after the training, we are not asked to handle the right tasks.

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:35.320
Some of those tasks might not even be covered in the training. They may look similar, though.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:40.279
Even if you were able to avoid the first two, you may still end up in the last situation

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:46.400
where you have a grand plan of what to do with your project using R, but have to go

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:53.559
back to the old ways because your deadline is the same. Now, unfortunately, before realizing

00:01:53.559 --> 00:01:58.879
any of these, we assumed everything would work after the training. When it didn't, we

00:01:58.879 --> 00:02:03.519
just thought we need to work harder on the next one. In fact, in one of those follow-up

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:08.960
training I provided, I even remade the lion king song into can you use the R tonight,

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:14.279
summarizing the R functions we talked about, but it still did not help. It turns out what

00:02:14.279 --> 00:02:19.520
we need is to create a soft landing that will start small and help the team to build

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:27.360
confidence, identify the task for them, and plan the effort for the transition. My soft

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:32.759
landing idea then was to build a work automation project using R, and next I'm going to talk

00:02:32.759 --> 00:02:38.139
about the six key parts of the project, and in the end, you will see why that was perfect

00:02:38.139 --> 00:02:43.660
for this situation. So to build an automation project, first,

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:48.979
let's look into what's possible. At that time, I was a member of a data team, and for most

00:02:48.979 --> 00:02:54.820
data teams on this planet, you cannot escape from reports. So let's take a look at a typical

00:02:54.820 --> 00:03:02.580
report. If we can describe it step by step, like traveling on a map, you first open your

00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:07.860
map, maybe it's a SQL database, data lake, all that. Then you update your parameter and

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:16.059
run. Then you wait. Export the data, clean the results, analyze it, update the format,

00:03:16.059 --> 00:03:21.580
draft an email, and send. But then if you look again, it almost looks like all of these

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:28.740
steps can be divided into three portions where we just use different groups of application.

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:32.740
For some of those reports, I would start with Oracle, move on to Excel, and then end

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:39.100
it with Outlook. For other reports, I would just use other applications. But regardless

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:43.899
of the difference of those applications, we all seem to start from getting the data. Then

00:03:43.899 --> 00:03:50.020
do the data wrangling, analysis, visualization, and end it with communication. So if you have

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:55.699
a report that has any parts that fits any of those three portions, we can replace that

00:03:55.699 --> 00:04:01.619
portion with R code with the help of those R packages. And the good thing is, there are

00:04:01.619 --> 00:04:07.339
so many of these R packages. Now, this makes sense for the reports that

00:04:07.339 --> 00:04:12.699
would take some efforts. But how about the processes whose pain point was running the

00:04:12.699 --> 00:04:18.019
task itself and sharing the result on a daily basis? How about the stakeholder requests

00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:23.980
where we just require you to run a SQL query and share the data? Well, they still fit in

00:04:24.019 --> 00:04:28.739
the scope of this automation project. We just need a little bit more help.

00:04:28.739 --> 00:04:33.940
When defining automation, there are three types. So the first type are the one perfect

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:40.380
for the reports that will still need some human involvement. And that would be perfect

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:45.739
to be done with R code. The second type are the ones that are good for the process that

00:04:45.739 --> 00:04:52.140
does not necessarily need human input, but will need to happen at a certain time. And

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:58.380
that would be best with R plus RStudio Connect. Lastly, also my favorite, a combination of

00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:03.940
the previous two. In this case, the human input will come from stakeholder, and they

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:09.380
can kick off whatever processes that will get them the answer with the help of Shiny.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:17.100
Now, if we look at these definitions, none of those are new. But the current R ecosystem

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:22.859
was able to offer a brand new interpretation. So after knowing what can be done in the project

00:05:22.859 --> 00:05:29.980
and what the current R ecosystem can help you with, time to sell it to decision makers.

00:05:29.980 --> 00:05:34.899
And whenever you're selling something, you want to talk about its benefits. So what are

00:05:34.899 --> 00:05:43.140
the benefits here? Reproducibility. The first word popping in my head. Then we may get last

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:47.779
human error if we code everything correctly. And if we were able to achieve the first two,

00:05:47.779 --> 00:05:55.019
we were able to be able to save some time. So I got a few decision makers in the room,

00:05:55.019 --> 00:05:59.980
presented them my plan of automating all the tasks identified in step one, along with the

00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:06.339
benefits here. If I could replicate the third interest level using a gauge here. So when

00:06:06.339 --> 00:06:10.899
I first talk about reproducibility, I gave them an example. If I'm out of office, someone

00:06:10.899 --> 00:06:16.899
else can run all the tasks that I'm handling. Their interest level wasn't very high. Maybe

00:06:16.899 --> 00:06:22.579
because it sounded very similar to a travel insurance, where it is not urgent at the moment.

00:06:22.579 --> 00:06:28.540
You would only miss it after things happen. Then I moved on with last human error, but

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:33.420
not additional interest because maybe they were thinking it is all theoretical and code

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:39.859
is written by human, too. Lastly, hours saved. More interests? And then they even asked me

00:06:39.859 --> 00:06:46.059
if I have any numbers. But overall, I did not get the go ahead. This is when I realized

00:06:46.059 --> 00:06:53.100
I was so ready and so prepared to sell this whole thing to our user, who is more concerned

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:57.859
about the day-to-day workflow, but not decision makers who have no programming experience

00:06:57.859 --> 00:07:03.459
and who is more concerned about the return on investment as well as business urgencies.

00:07:03.459 --> 00:07:09.700
So I waited a few weeks, just after everybody forgot about what I said, and updated my strategy

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:16.059
and this is what I presented. So I started with hours saved. In fact, I told them if

00:07:16.059 --> 00:07:22.459
we go through with this, we might be able to save 1,000 hours per year. They're interested.

00:07:22.459 --> 00:07:28.779
Then I moved on to last human error. If we code everything correctly, they're still intrigued.

00:07:28.779 --> 00:07:34.899
Lastly, I sold reproducibility like a free add-on travel insurance. Who would have loved

00:07:34.899 --> 00:07:40.540
that? Overall, we got the go ahead. But then if you look back, it is still the same number

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:45.220
of benefits, just in a slightly different order. I guess sometimes it makes sense for

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:50.540
us to start with the one that does not require too much context to understand. And now you

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:55.940
see why I named the talk saving 1,000 hours with RStudio, not bringing reproducibility

00:07:55.940 --> 00:07:59.619
with RStudio. If that was the talk name, I don't know if half of you would show up or

00:07:59.619 --> 00:08:06.140
even I would show up. So after getting the decision makers buy-in, time to get the things

00:08:06.140 --> 00:08:12.299
we need to do the actual automation. High level, there are two things. A document of

00:08:12.299 --> 00:08:16.420
the current process so that we know what needs to be done and information for us to compare

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:22.260
all the tasks so that we know which one to start with. To get the documentation, we will

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:27.179
need to understand the current processes. Well, you may say, wouldn't that just need

00:08:27.179 --> 00:08:32.260
tools and steps? Mostly, yes. But we will also need to understand the business reasons

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:37.739
so that we can accommodate any changes that may end up making the process better. We will

00:08:37.739 --> 00:08:43.460
also need to understand the occurrence, whether it happens daily, weekly, or ad hoc so that

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:48.659
we can choose the best platform or tool for it. Lastly, we tend to forget communication

00:08:48.659 --> 00:08:53.859
is part of the automation. And I would always recommend saving a few communication examples

00:08:53.859 --> 00:08:59.419
in your document. On top of that, we also want to know the current efforts in terms

00:08:59.419 --> 00:09:05.820
of the overall time for each run before the automation. And what's the manual versus processing

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:13.140
time breakdown and identifying the tough items through this process. Ideally, the automation

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:18.940
should always work if we code things right. But oftentimes, it is not ideal, which is

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:23.700
why it is critical for us to know how often should we update the process of the document

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:30.780
so that we know when it will be obsolete. And oftentimes, we're not always the original

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:37.260
report owner. So, we need to know when to stop and call for additional help. Now, all

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:42.539
of these will get us a detailed document of the requirements. Of course, it's always a

00:09:42.539 --> 00:09:47.580
great opportunity to practice our markdown. But other than the document itself, we now

00:09:47.739 --> 00:09:55.820
know the complexity of potentially automating this process. The impact, as well as the stability,

00:09:55.820 --> 00:10:01.020
which would allow you to rank all your tasks in a table that looks like this. So, if you're

00:10:01.020 --> 00:10:05.979
wondering which one to start, you may not want to start with task number one, where it is

00:10:05.979 --> 00:10:11.500
complicated as small impact and may require you to update the code every other week. You may want

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:17.099
to consider starting from automating task number three, where it is not overly complicated,

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:22.859
earning you some recognition, and there's less need for you to update the code. And then,

00:10:22.859 --> 00:10:28.219
maybe you can move on to the harder ones. After knowing what is needed, identifying the task to

00:10:28.219 --> 00:10:33.979
start with, time to roll up the sleeves. Now, to do the actual automation, there are so many

00:10:33.979 --> 00:10:38.619
things to cover here. In fact, I've been working on an automation book trying to cover all the

00:10:38.619 --> 00:10:43.820
common scenarios using two dozens of chapters. So, I will just be brief here with my top three

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:50.059
recommendations. My first recommendation is to always start with components. Let's just say if

00:10:50.059 --> 00:10:56.219
you have a process that separately involves SQL, Excel, and Outlook, you want to code them one by

00:10:56.219 --> 00:11:02.619
one because within the same team and organization, the same processes will involve the similar

00:11:02.619 --> 00:11:07.979
components where you can just reuse the code. My second recommendation is that we should

00:11:07.979 --> 00:11:13.979
definitely do plenty of tasks to capture all the scenarios possible. Whether it be dependency

00:11:13.979 --> 00:11:21.659
tasks, user tasks, dev tasks, unit tasks, we should do all the applicable ones. I know everybody

00:11:21.659 --> 00:11:26.380
trusts their own code. I do, too. But the reality has taught me to trust the tasks even more.

00:11:27.580 --> 00:11:34.940
Lastly, be practical and stay on target. I know it feels great to be able to build all

00:11:34.940 --> 00:11:40.380
solutions within R. But the thing is, not everything needs to be fully automated. At the

00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:46.460
end of the day, it is not about building something cool with R, but building something impactful

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:52.140
with R. I've got lost in that so many times. So, let me say this again. It is not about building

00:11:52.140 --> 00:11:59.419
something cool with R, but building something impactful with R. Now, after the coding task is

00:11:59.419 --> 00:12:05.099
all done, we can hand off the process and move on. But there are still things we need to look

00:12:05.099 --> 00:12:11.900
out for in order to keep the project going. Overall, there are three deadly situations

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:18.539
that could affect your project. The first situation is that after you handed off your

00:12:18.539 --> 00:12:24.859
automated processes, someone ran the code. But the result isn't what's expected. Maybe because

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:31.340
the script wasn't handled properly, like running it on a new machine or a new environment without

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:35.820
the proper setup. Believe it or not, after all these years, it still happens to me.

00:12:37.099 --> 00:12:42.780
So, to avoid this situation, what I would recommend is to always have a handout document

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:46.619
that discusses the requirements of the job, instructions of running the process,

00:12:46.619 --> 00:12:53.419
testing the process, and what to do to maintain. The second scenario is that as you build more and

00:12:53.419 --> 00:12:59.419
more automated processes, chances are multiple processes may run into issues at the same time.

00:13:00.219 --> 00:13:06.780
And sometimes someone will come up and need your help to fix it. Sometimes multiple people will

00:13:06.780 --> 00:13:13.979
show up, which could look pressing. So, my tip for you is this. Always discuss the fail safe

00:13:13.979 --> 00:13:20.460
in your handoff document. In most cases, a line like this will do the trick. This is almost like

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:24.780
when the autopilot stopped working. You don't stop flying or driving. You switch back to manual.

00:13:25.419 --> 00:13:31.340
And this often reduces the urgency and gives us the time to properly fix the issue.

00:13:32.619 --> 00:13:39.419
Lastly, everything went well. You just got a new feature request. Should you directly jump in?

00:13:40.539 --> 00:13:44.619
And my recommendation here, well, two recommendations. The short term is that

00:13:44.619 --> 00:13:50.059
always treat it like a brand new task so that you can start from gathering requirements and

00:13:50.219 --> 00:13:56.460
best determine when to work on it. And then the longer term solution here is that it is also a

00:13:56.460 --> 00:14:01.340
perfect opportunity for you to train your individual team members to gradually take on the task and

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:07.020
accumulate more knowledge. Now, after you're comfortable with dealing with those three

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:13.739
situations, we just need to give it time for the project to make progress. And just like any of the

00:14:13.739 --> 00:14:20.859
other projects, from time to time, you want to share updates. And to do that, I often find it

00:14:20.859 --> 00:14:25.739
helpful to start with the key stats. For example, hours saved, which is something you can easily

00:14:25.739 --> 00:14:30.619
extract from the requirement document that you have built in the previous steps. And the number

00:14:30.619 --> 00:14:35.979
of process documents now available because of this project. As well as the all the training

00:14:35.979 --> 00:14:39.820
that happened because throughout this project, whether it would be the official one or the

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:44.619
one on one sessions that you had with your team members. On top of that, you also want to share

00:14:44.619 --> 00:14:49.900
any of the success stories, learnings that happened along the way. And maybe give kudos to your team

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:54.859
member that you collaborated with. And lastly, you don't want to forget talking about the hurdles

00:14:55.419 --> 00:15:01.739
where you could use additional help on. Other than that, you also want to determine a good cadence

00:15:01.739 --> 00:15:06.859
to share progress. For me, it was once a month. But you should always set up your own and know

00:15:06.859 --> 00:15:15.659
that you can share progress whenever you have critical updates. Now, that wraps up the key parts

00:15:15.659 --> 00:15:20.619
of the project. If you would like to start something similar at your workplace, this is

00:15:20.619 --> 00:15:26.940
a structure you could follow. First, start from identifying the task in your workplace. Then,

00:15:27.900 --> 00:15:33.580
build your proposal with the benefits that would matter to your decision makers and workplace.

00:15:34.539 --> 00:15:40.059
After that, build a requirement document with possibly with R Markdown, identify the right task

00:15:40.059 --> 00:15:47.820
to start with. Then, code by component. Do plenty of tasks. And stay on target.

00:15:49.099 --> 00:15:52.539
While at the same time, try to stay away from the three deadly situations.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:16:00.780
And don't forget to share progress from time to time. Now, I would like to ask everyone to

00:16:00.780 --> 00:16:06.299
think back about the original situation. As we build more and more automated processes,

00:16:06.859 --> 00:16:13.580
we have completely moved on from the original question of why the R adoption rate isn't what's

00:16:13.580 --> 00:16:19.659
expected after the R training to now having most team members owning several of these R processes

00:16:19.659 --> 00:16:25.580
where they were at least involved in building the requirements, testing the process, and execution.

00:16:26.539 --> 00:16:32.219
Rather than expecting everyone to connect the R functionalities to the business needs through the

00:16:32.219 --> 00:16:39.340
R training, we connect the business needs to the R functionalities through this project. And we just

00:16:39.340 --> 00:16:45.580
happen to save thousands of hours. Now, if you're a decision maker in this room, this might be a

00:16:45.580 --> 00:16:51.979
good project to make some impact and accumulate some R knowledge. If you're a team member in this

00:16:51.979 --> 00:16:57.580
room, bring this back and start from identifying the tasks. If you're one of the two team members

